'''Camiri''' (Camirito, La Bomba, Choreti, Capital Petrolera de Bolivia) is a city in [[Bolivia]], [[Santa Cruz Department (Bolivia)|Santa Cruz Department]], [[Cordillera Province (Bolivia)|Cordillera Province]]. It is the seat of the Camiri Municipality. The town has an estimated population of 65,897 inhabitants,<ref>[http://world-gazetteer.com/wg.php?x=&men=gcis&lng=en&des=wg&geo=-38&srt=npan&col=adhoq&msz=1500 World Gazetteer] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111120144113/http://world-gazetteer.com/wg.php?x=&men=gcis&lng=en&des=wg&geo=-38&srt=npan&col=adhoq&msz=1500 |date=2011-11-20 }}</ref> also known as "Camireños." Camiri is on the banks of the [[Parapeti River]] in a small valley surrounded by rolling hills on the east, north, and south, and by the [[Serranía del Aguaragüe|Aguarague mountain range]] on the west.
Camiri's "Chaco" ecosystem encompasses [[subtropics|subtropical]] dry forests with low [[canopy (forest)|canopy]], and intense [[xerophile|xerophilic]] overgrowth with a large [[biodiversity|diversity]] of wildlife.
On February 3, 2007, local protesters shut down a natural gas pipeline in Camiri that serves southern Bolivia. The protesters were seeking an expansion of the nationalization of the natural gas industry and a renewal of the promise of construction of facilities for [[YPFB]], the national petroleum company.
==Climate== [[File:Camiri Parque Central Dic 2011.JPG|thumb|left|220px|Central park]] [[File:Camiri Central Park.JPG|thumb|left|220px|Statue in the Central park]] Camiri has a [[humid subtropical climate]] ([[Köppen climate classification|Köppen]]: ''Cwa'').
